Temptations may be encountered‚ by applying their opposites: as when an individua] is observed to be disposed to pride, he should be employed in the more abject occupations which may seem good to humble him, and so of the other depraved propensities of the soul.

Moreover, it is a matter of propriety and decency, that no woman enter our Houses and Colleges, but our Churches only; and that neither arms nor other instruments of vanity be allowed, but only those things which conduce to the object which the Society has in view, the service and praise of God. What measure should be observed in enjoining penances and corrections, must be left to the prudent charity of the Superior, and those whom he has deputed: who in these matters will regard the dispositions of persons, and the general and individual edifi- cation to the glory of God.
